are given by polynomials involving
𝑥&nbsp;

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:31.600
x and
𝑦&nbsp;

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:37.680
y. So, they're reasonably pleasant algebraic&nbsp;
objects—there should be a pleasant calculus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:43.040
for them too. Of course, that brings&nbsp;
up the question: Well, what exactly are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:49.680
we talking about here when we talk about&nbsp;
an algebraic curve? What does that mean?

00:04:49.680 --> 00:04:53.720
So, let's have a historical look at&nbsp;
these questions by going back to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:58.040
ancient Greeks to start with and having&nbsp;
a look at what they were thinking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:04.360
in the context of curves. Greek mathematics&nbsp;
emphasizes the importance of the straightedge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:09.000
and compass for making geometrical&nbsp;
constructions and, correspondingly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:16.520
the notions of line and circle as being the&nbsp;
fundamental curves or mathematical objects out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:26.640
of which most other things are built. So, those&nbsp;
are the primary curves in Greek mathematics.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:33.360
Then, sort of one level up, they discovered the&nbsp;
conic sections. The conic sections are obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:41.320
by essentially combining the circle and the line&nbsp;
to get a cone. The cone is what you get when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.320 --> 00:05:47.680
take a circle and then a point not in the plane&nbsp;
of that circle and draw all the lines from that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:53.920
point to the various points on the circle—you&nbsp;
get a cone. And then the conic sections are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.920 --> 00:06:01.680
obtained by slicing that cone with a plane. If you&nbsp;
slice the cone with a plane in that orientation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:08.520
you get an elliptical cross-section. If you&nbsp;
slice it with a plane something like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:16.640
then you cut both the top and the bottom parts&nbsp;
of the cone to get a hyperbolic cross-section,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:21.440
or hyperbola. And then, sort of halfway&nbsp;
between these, poised between them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:27.440
is the case when the plane is just&nbsp;
parallel to one of the lines of the cone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:36.560
so it cuts the cone only in one of its&nbsp;
parts, and that way you get a parabola.

00:06:36.560 --> 00:06:41.320
So, these are the three standard kinds of&nbsp;
conic sections, but there are, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:47.440
degenerate ones as well. We could also consider&nbsp;
the case when the plane slices right through&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:53.680
this point here in such a way that it also,&nbsp;
say, slices through those two lines there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.680 --> 00:07:04.280
forming an "X." So, a pair of intersecting&nbsp;
lines is also a conic section. In fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:09.560
if we took a plane that went like this,&nbsp;
then we would be just picking up one line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.560 --> 00:07:16.080
so one line—one might think of it as a doubled&nbsp;
line—is also a conic section. And the most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:21.720
degenerate case is when you take a plane that just&nbsp;
slices the cone at its vertex there—then you're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:31.640
only picking up a single point. So, this notion&nbsp;
of conic sections does have degenerate cases too.

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:38.320
These were well studied by Archimedes and&nbsp;
Apollonius prominently, and the ancient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:44.800
Greeks learned a lot about them. But they also&nbsp;
considered quite a few other curves, some of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:52.280
them very interesting. For example, Archimedes&nbsp;
introduced the idea of a spiral, and he thought&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.280 --> 00:08:01.280
very mechanically, physically. He imagined a line&nbsp;
that was fixed at a point rotating uniformly about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:07.920
that point—actually, sort of a ray, I guess—and&nbsp;
then imagined on that line a particle moving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:16.160
linearly along that line at the same time that&nbsp;
the ray is rotating. Okay, so if the particle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:23.200
starts there, then after a little while it's&nbsp;
here, and then it's there, sort of trying to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:31.840
follow it roughly something like this. So you get&nbsp;
this spiral shape, which goes on indefinitely,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:39.200
and he proved some very nice things about it.&nbsp;
These days it's most easily described in polar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:47.840
coordinates using the radius and theta and has&nbsp;
a relatively simple equation in terms of those.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:54.080
There's the cissoid of Diocles, which is&nbsp;
obtained from a circle, and here are two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.080 --> 00:09:01.200
perpendicular diameters of the circle. From this&nbsp;
point here, we go an equal arc in this direction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.600
and in this direction. So, once we've gone equal&nbsp;
amounts in this direction and this direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:12.440
we take the line perpendicular to&nbsp;
this diameter through that point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:18.000
and then we connect this point with that&nbsp;
point there to obtain the intersection right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.880
there. As we change these two points,&nbsp;
making them wider or further apart,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:29.400
