00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:06.640
Then there was the conchoid of Nicomedes, which&nbsp;
was also around 200 BC, and it's also something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:12.480
that's reasonably natural. It's also formed by&nbsp;
lines, so we have a fixed line there, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.480 --> 00:10:18.320
a fixed point here, and then we're considering&nbsp;
the various lines going through our fixed point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:27.440
and we're looking at going a fixed length&nbsp;
from the baseline on any one of these lines.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:34.320
So, on any one of these lines, we then go a&nbsp;
fixed length in the direction from the line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:39.560
okay, and then these points trace out some&nbsp;
curve, which will sort of asymptotically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:47.040
approach the line as we go out in that direction,&nbsp;
and that's the conchoid of Nicomedes. I think he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:53.680
actually made a mechanical construction that&nbsp;
would actually draw this thing for you. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.680 --> 00:10:59.240
the ancient Greeks did think in terms of&nbsp;
mechanical constructions for their curves.

00:11:00.160 --> 00:11:05.720
Another kind of curve that was considered are&nbsp;
the spheric sections, where you get a torus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.720 --> 00:11:12.720
and a torus, or a donut, is what you get when you&nbsp;
take a circle and you rotate it around an axis.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:19.040
So, this has a circular cross-section, and this is&nbsp;
also a circular direction here, so we're rotating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:24.520
a circle around a circle to get a donut. And&nbsp;
then these spheric sections are the curves that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:24.520 --> 00:11:31.120
you get by slicing this donut with a plane, and&nbsp;
the various curves that you get depend very much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.120 --> 00:11:38.040
on where the plane is in relation to the donut.&nbsp;
You can get a pair of circles, or you get kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:43.960
an oval shape, or a curve that kind of indents a&nbsp;
little bit, or a very interesting sort of special&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:50.120
case is when the curve is such that it crosses&nbsp;
there, and you get a sort of figure-8 curve.

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:55.040
Of course, ancient peoples were very interested in&nbsp;
astronomy, and in particular, figuring out what's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:55.040 --> 00:12:02.200
going on with the planets in the night sky. To&nbsp;
understand that, Ptolemy introduced the notion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:10.160
of an epicycle, which is a curve that's formed&nbsp;
when one circle rotates about another circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:16.440
and we're watching the image of a point. So,&nbsp;
if this point rotates, if the circle rotates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:25.480
then the trajectory of such a point is something&nbsp;
like this, looping around the bigger circle.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:29.760
Alright, so the ancient Greeks had a variety of&nbsp;
curves that they were interested in, and they had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:29.760 --> 00:12:36.880
both a mechanical and geometrical understanding&nbsp;
of these curves. The next really important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:43.280
development is in the time of the Europeans&nbsp;
around the 17th century with René Descartes and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:52.320
his fundamental treatise La Géométrie, in which&nbsp;
he introduces the idea of algebraic coordinates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:52.320 --> 00:13:00.960
to deal with geometrical problems. It's from this&nbsp;
that we get our notion of Cartesian coordinates,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:07.880
with an x-axis, a y-axis, equally spaced&nbsp;
labels along each axis, and the idea that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.880 --> 00:13:14.640
you can represent a curve by an equation,&nbsp;
and conversely, given an equation, you can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:22.440
picture it by a curve. An absolutely fundamental&nbsp;
innovation and advance in mathematics—probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:29.080
in pure mathematics, perhaps one of the most&nbsp;
important innovations in the last 500 years.

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:34.920
Descartes realized that the power of this&nbsp;
point of view was that the algebra tells&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:41.080
you a lot about the curve, and you can calculate&nbsp;
purely algebraically instead of having to make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.080 --> 00:13:48.120
geometrical constructions. He realized that if&nbsp;
you took the simplest possible relation between&nbsp;

