00:14:30.634 --> 00:14:40.160
(x,y) traces out a conic, and every conic can be&nbsp;
expressed in this form. So, this is an incredibly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:46.080
exciting development—he could then see how to&nbsp;
prove pretty much everything that Apollonius&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:53.520
knew about conics by working with the algebraic&nbsp;
representation of them. He also saw that there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:53.520 --> 00:15:00.920
a natural hierarchy of curves depending&nbsp;
on the degree—that's the linear degree 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:06.760
that's quadratic degree 2—so there's a natural&nbsp;
progression of complexity of curves depending&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.760 --> 00:15:13.520
on the degree. One can't underestimate&nbsp;
the importance of this development.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:18.600
So, I think anybody who's mathematically minded&nbsp;
when they hear about this story naturally they're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.600 --> 00:15:24.720
going to ask, well, alright, if degree 2 curves&nbsp;
are the conic sections of the ancient Greeks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:33.000
what are the degree 3 curves? Absolutely natural,&nbsp;
obvious question—what do they look like? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:38.520
people were interested, of course, and Isaac&nbsp;
Newton, famous for many things, of course&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:45.680
including the development of the calculus and&nbsp;
the laws of motion, including resolution of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:52.960
conundrum of how the planets move, investigated&nbsp;
cubic curves with the idea of taking a general&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:59.440
cubic curve, which rather has this long,&nbsp;
intimidating structure. So it's a combination of&nbsp;

