those equations and said, well, if I graph that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:19.960
what am I going to get? What does it look&nbsp;
like? And he made various transformations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:25.600
to try to get them into sort of standard&nbsp;
forms. Just as there are more or less three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:25.600 --> 00:16:32.200
conics—at least three non-degenerate conics—he&nbsp;
tried to analyze how many cubics there were,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:39.240
and I think his list has some 70 or 80 in&nbsp;
it. It wasn't completely correct, but anyway,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:44.440
the cubic story is much more involved than&nbsp;
the conic story, but still very interesting.

00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:51.120
So, here's just some brief indication of what&nbsp;
cubics can look like. So, in black here, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:59.680
a possible shape of a cubic. See, it actually has&nbsp;
two components, or it could look like this thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.680 --> 00:17:06.600
here, or it could look like this with sort of a&nbsp;
cusp, or it could look like a bunch of branches,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:13.280
maybe even with an isolated point, or it&nbsp;
could have even three branches like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:19.840
There's quite a lot of possibilities for what&nbsp;
a cubic looks like, and of course, then there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.840 --> 00:17:24.960
the corresponding question: Well, what about the&nbsp;
higher degree curves? Once we've understood cubics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:30.800
more or less, what about quartics—fourth-degree&nbsp;
curves—or quintics—fifth-degree curves—and so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:37.840
on? And I have to say that, of course, nowadays,&nbsp;
this is subsumed in algebraic geometry, but it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.840 --> 00:17:45.360
a bit of a mystery to me why algebraic geometers&nbsp;
don't spend more time and energy explaining to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.360 --> 00:17:51.280
the rest of us what the answers to this natural&nbsp;
question are. I think it'd be lovely to have more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:59.200
pictures of algebraic curves so we can see some&nbsp;
of the variety and the beauty of these objects.

00:17:59.200 --> 00:18:03.320
Actually, there's a reason why they don't&nbsp;
do that, partially, but we'll get to that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.320 --> 00:18:08.080
later when we talk more about algebraic&nbsp;
geometry. But you can see here that, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.080 --> 00:18:13.760
these kinds of curves that result&nbsp;
from thinking about the degree of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:14.640
polynomial in
𝑥&nbsp;

00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:15.160
x and
𝑦&nbsp;

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:20.960
y in a Cartesian setting introduced by&nbsp;
Descartes—very reasonable, very natural,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:20.960 --> 00:18:28.480
perhaps very pleasant field of investigation. But&nbsp;
there's a lot more to curves than these things.

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:34.200
So, the 17th and 18th centuries saw a lot of work&nbsp;
and development of not just the algebraic curves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:40.160
that we've been talking about, but also other&nbsp;
kinds of curves that had often a mechanical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:48.280
formulation. For example, a catenary, which&nbsp;
is the shape formed by a hanging chain. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:53.560
you get a chain and you hang it from two equally&nbsp;
spaced points—you get some kind of curve, and it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:59.200
natural to ask, what is the shape of that curve?&nbsp;
People thought maybe originally it was a parabola,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:05.320
and it's maybe reasonably close to a parabola, but&nbsp;
it's actually a different curve called a catenary.

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:12.120
Another important curve that's related to motion&nbsp;
is what happens when you roll a circle on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:18.160
line—it's just like Ptolemy's epicycles except&nbsp;
that the rolling circle is rolling on a line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:24.800
instead of a bigger circle. So, if we choose some&nbsp;
point on the circle and we follow its path as our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.800 --> 00:19:33.040
given circle rolls, it's going to form something&nbsp;
that looks like this—that's called a cycloid.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:39.600
And that cycloid had a lot of remarkable&nbsp;
properties—it was not an algebraic curve,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:47.720
but people eventually realized that it had&nbsp;
a lot to do with the laws of motion. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:52.400
if you invert a cycloid—in other words, just&nbsp;
turn it upside down—instead of having a branch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:57.720
like this, we have a branch like this, then&nbsp;
if we think of the motion of a particle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:57.720 --> 00:20:05.400
like a ball rolling down that curve, this has&nbsp;
two very interesting properties. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:12.600
it's what's called the tautochrone, meaning&nbsp;
equal time curve. And what that means is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.600 --> 00:20:17.920
that if you start the ball anywhere along&nbsp;
this curve, anywhere from here up to here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:24.480
and you drop it and let it roll down—assuming&nbsp;
there's no friction—then the amount of time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:31.040
that it takes to get there is fixed. So, it takes&nbsp;
the same amount of time to roll down from the top&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:39.560
as it does from here or even from here. It's a&nbsp;
remarkable property of the inverted cycloid. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:46.360
then another property is the brachistochrone&nbsp;
property—that's actually the shortest time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:54.800
curve. If you want to slide down a slide from this&nbsp;
point to this point and you consider all possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:54.800 --> 00:21:00.480
curves between these two points, including, for&nbsp;
example, a straight line, which is an obvious or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:06.680
a very primitive kind of slide, then it turns out&nbsp;
that exactly this inverted cycloid is the curve&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:13.440
that lets the ball go down fastest—anything&nbsp;
else that you choose will be slightly or much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:20.360
slower. And the names associated with these&nbsp;
results are Huygens and Jacob Bernoulli,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:28.840
Jacob being one of the many Bernoulli brothers&nbsp;
that played an important role in mathematics.

00:21:28.840 --> 00:21:37.360
Alright, so the Europeans were very fascinated&nbsp;
by curves, and they had both an algebraic and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:42.160
a mechanical orientation to them. But even&nbsp;
going back to the founder, to Descartes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:47.200
Descartes realized that one should make a&nbsp;
distinction—that there was something special&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:53.440
about the algebraic curves that were given by&nbsp;
polynomials. And he sort of had this division&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:59.960
into mechanical and geometrical—these days people&nbsp;
say algebraic versus transcendental, perhaps,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:05.440
but it's more or less the same thing. So, the idea&nbsp;
that the algebraic curves given by polynomials&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:14.320
are in some sense more amenable to analysis and&nbsp;
investigation than these transcendental curves.

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:18.840
But still, it begs the question: What exactly are&nbsp;
we talking about here when we're talking about a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:25.040
curve? So, it's a rather subtle question of&nbsp;
what exactly is a curve, and historically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:29.600
it's caused quite a lot of problems, and&nbsp;
there's been a lot of debate and a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:33.720
introspection and analysis of figuring out what&nbsp;
exactly we are talking about when we're talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:38.680
about a curve. It's easy enough to put our pen&nbsp;
down on paper and squiggle around a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:43.200
and get something and say, well, that's&nbsp;
a curve. But what exactly are we doing?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:50.000
How are we mathematically modeling that?&nbsp;
What is allowed, and what is not allowed?

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:54.840
It's rather surprising that the modern&nbsp;
definition only really took place in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:54.840 --> 00:23:02.080
around the last part of the 19th century. In&nbsp;
the 1880s, Jordan gave this following modern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:07.360
definition of a curve. He said that a curve is&nbsp;
a set of points taken on by a pair of continuous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.360 --> 00:23:09.000
functions
𝑥&nbsp;

