00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:47.520
Okay, this is a very unfortunate&nbsp;
definition—it's a completely wrong idea,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.520 --> 00:23:55.840
it's very wrong thinking, and it's far too&nbsp;
simplistic, and it's logically just cheating,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.840 --> 00:24:03.040
as we'll see. But there was already evidence&nbsp;
shortly after Jordan gave his definition that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.040 --> 00:24:08.200
there was something fishy going on here.&nbsp;
Just a few years afterward, in 1890,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:16.440
Peano gave an example where a curve, which is a&nbsp;
curve by Jordan's definition, had a remarkable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:24.920
in fact almost absurd, quality. So, he showed&nbsp;
that you could cook up two continuous functions,&nbsp;

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:25.280
𝑓
(&nbsp;

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:25.555
