00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:38.680
interval from 0 to 1 onto the square in such a way&nbsp;
that it was one-to-one and onto and continuous.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:44.080
That means that there's actually a bijection,&nbsp;
so this curve, which is not like this—this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.080 --> 00:24:52.520
some kind of simplistic rendition of it—but&nbsp;
this curve, whatever it is, takes every point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:52.520 --> 00:24:59.320
here to every point here in a one-to-one way,&nbsp;
so that the curve as the set of points obtained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.320 --> 00:25:08.800
is actually the unit square. So, according to&nbsp;
Jordan's definition, the unit square is a curve.

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:13.360
Okay, so most people, when looking&nbsp;
at this example, would say, alright,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:13.360 --> 00:25:19.840
well that just proves that the definition is&nbsp;
wrong. If I have a definition of a circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:28.040
for example, and we ultimately decide that a&nbsp;
lemniscate is a circle according to my definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:28.040 --> 00:25:33.200
then the natural deduction is that my definition&nbsp;
is not a very good one—that we should forget&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:33.200 --> 00:25:39.200
about it and try something else. That would&nbsp;
have been the natural deduction to make from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:47.720
Peano's example. And then other people gave other&nbsp;
examples, including Hilbert. But convenience took&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:57.840
precedence over logical clarity. These days, the&nbsp;
definition of a curve is more or less this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:57.840 --> 00:26:03.520
except that people have changed their tune just&nbsp;
slightly to say, okay, the curve is not actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:03.520 --> 00:26:14.360
the image, it's actually the pair of functions,&nbsp;
so the pair of functions is the curve. But still,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.360 --> 00:26:22.560
Peano's curve is still a curve in the modern&nbsp;
definition. Students are usually not shown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:27.000
this in an introductory calculus class&nbsp;
because it's a little bit embarrassing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.960
just as it was embarrassing in the last part of&nbsp;
the 19th century. A lot of embarrassing things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.960 --> 00:26:37.840
happened in the last part of the 19th century, by&nbsp;
the way, okay? Things that are still casting their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:42.600
shadow over modern mathematics—we're&nbsp;
going to talk a lot more about them.

00:26:42.600 --> 00:26:48.760
So, if the notion of a curve is perhaps&nbsp;
at this point too ambitious, perhaps we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:48.760 --> 00:26:54.720
should scale down our intentions and try to&nbsp;
do something more modest. Why don't we stick&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:54.720 --> 00:27:01.840
with algebraic curves just the way Descartes&nbsp;
urged us to do? That's much more amenable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:08.680
much more treatable with logical clarity,&nbsp;
and there's a natural way forward going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.680 --> 00:27:13.080
back to Descartes and Newton and&nbsp;
the pioneers of the subject. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:19.520
an excellent way of starting to think about&nbsp;
curves is by using the framework of bipolynomials.

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:25.040
Let me remind you that a bipolynomial is a&nbsp;
