00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:59.160
Okay, so you can see some of the complicated&nbsp;
issues that are related to this notion. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:04.800
this is a course in foundations of mathematics,&nbsp;
and so these kinds of issues are bread and butter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:04.800 --> 00:33:12.520
for us—we're going to want to examine this in&nbsp;
great detail. We want to get this right. Most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:18.480
of modern mathematics tries to hurry-scurry&nbsp;
its way past these foundational issues—quick,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:18.480 --> 00:33:24.520
quick, quick, do it very fast, then we'll talk&nbsp;
about something else. Not us. We're interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:31.640
in going very slowly, very carefully, making&nbsp;
sure we understand what exactly is going on.

00:33:31.640 --> 00:33:38.600
Next time, I'm going to introduce an important&nbsp;
idea that will be necessary for us to really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:38.600 --> 00:33:43.560
understand what a curve is. I'm going to talk&nbsp;
about the difference between 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:50.200
mathematics and 21st-century mathematics.&nbsp;
20th-century mathematics is behind us;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:50.200 --> 00:33:55.280
21st-century mathematics is largely in the&nbsp;
future. There's going to be a big difference,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:55.280 --> 00:33:59.600
and I'm going to talk about an aspect of&nbsp;
what I believe that big difference is—the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:59.600 --> 00:34:06.120
difference between object-oriented mathematics&nbsp;
and expression-oriented mathematics. Then we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:11.680
going to see that that's quite pertinent to this&nbsp;
question of how exactly do we go about setting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:11.680 --> 00:34:18.720
out what a curve is, what an algebraic curve&nbsp;
is, and how we do calculus with such things.

00:34:18.720 --> 00:34:27.720
So, I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

